solution.p:
Using x=-3 and y=4, we find r=\sqrt{3^2 + 4^2} = \sqrt{25} = 5 so \cos \theta = \dfrac{x}{r} = \dfrac{-3}{5}, and \theta = \cos^{-1}(\dfrac{-3}{5}). We can enter 
     \text{2nd   COS}~~~ -3/5~ ) ~~~\text{ENTER } 
to see that \theta \approx 126.9 \degree.

warning.p:
In the previous example, you might notice that \tan \theta = \dfrac{-4}{3} and try to find  by calculating \tan^{-1}(\dfrac{-4}{3}). However, if we press  
     \text{2nd   TAN}~~~ -4/3~ ) ~~~\text{ENTER }  
the calculator returns an angle of \theta \approx -53.1 \degree.  It is true that \tan (-53.1 \degree) = \dfrac{-4}{3}, but this is not the obtuse angle we want.

sidebyside.p:
We also know that \sin \theta = \dfrac{4}{5}, and if we press 
    \text{2nd   SIN}~~~ 4/5~ ) ~~~\text{ENTER } 
we get \theta \approx 53.1 \degree. This is the acute angle whose terminal side passes through the point (3,4), as shown in the figure at right.  The angle we want is its supplement, \theta \approx 180\degree - 53.1\degree = 126.9\degree.

